
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `hd` (hex dump) baraye namayesh dadan mohhtavayeh yek file be shekle hexadecimal va ASCII estefade mishavad. In dastoor baraye didan data-ye binary ya file-haye digar ke ghabl-khani nistand mofid ast.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `hd filename` --> 📄 Namayesh mohhtavayeh file be shekle hex va ASCII.
    🔹 `hd -n number filename` --> 🔢 Namayesh `number` byte az file.
    🔹 `hd -s offset filename` --> 📍 Shoru az offset moshakhas shode dar file.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ hd example.txt

    🔹 Namayesh mohhtavayeh file `example.txt` be shekle hex va ASCII.

    $ hd -n 16 example.bin

    🔹 Namayesh faghat 16 byte az file `example.bin`.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ hd -n 32 data.dat

    🔹 In dastoor 32 byte avalieh az file `data.dat` ra be shekle hexadecimal namayesh midahad, be shoma komak mikonad ta data-ye binary ra baresi konid.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `hd` (hex dump) command is used to display the content of a file in hexadecimal and ASCII formats. This is useful for inspecting binary data or other files that are not human-readable.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `hd filename` --> 📄 Display the contents of the file in hex and ASCII.
    🔹 `hd -n number filename` --> 🔢 Display only `number` bytes from the file.
    🔹 `hd -s offset filename` --> 📍 Start from the specified offset in the file.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ hd example.txt

    🔹 Display the contents of the `example.txt` file in hex and ASCII.

    $ hd -n 16 example.bin

    🔹 Display only the first 16 bytes of the `example.bin` file.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ hd -n 32 data.dat

    🔹 This command displays the first 32 bytes of the file `data.dat` in hexadecimal, helping you examine binary data.

